 from any of the places in Calvados and Seine-Maritime named Carville, from the Scandinavian personal name <i>Kári</i> + Old French <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of <b>Ó Cearbhaill</b> or <b>Mac Cearbhaill</b>, see   Carroll  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Carroll","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of <b>Ó Cearbhaill</b> or <b>Mac Cearbhaill</b> ‘descendant (or son) of <i>Cearbhall</i>’, a personal name perhaps based on <i>cearbh</i> ‘hacking’ and hence originally a byname for a butcher or a fierce warrior.","English and Scottish: variant of   Carrell  ."]},{"name":"Garfield","meanings":["English (Midlands): topographic name from Middle English <i>gor(e)</i>, <i>gar(e)</i> ‘triangular piece’ + <i>feld</i> ‘open country, field’ (Old English <i>gār</i> + <i>feld</i>), for someone who lived by a triangular piece of land.","English: alternatively, sometimes perhaps a variant of   Carville   (a name of Norman origin), with excrescent final <i>-d</i>.","Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames."]}]},{"name":"Felicia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["feminine form of   Felix .  It was popular in Britain in the medieval period (with the vernacular forms  <b>Felice</b> ,  <b>Felis</b> ), but by the 16th century it had become confused with   Phyllis .  In modern times it is in only occasional use."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":7,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":42,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wi